  "stage": {
    "id": "stage2_core",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Building the Artificial Hippocampus",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "openIE",
        "title": "Turning Text into Triples",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- subject-relation-object\n- LLM extraction\n\nHippoRAG uses an instruction-tuned LLM to extract schemaless triples from each passage, turning unstructured text into graph nodes (noun phrases) and edges (semantic relations).",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "knowledge_graph",
        "title": "The Hippocampal Index",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- corpus-wide graph\n- associative links\n\nThe KG is built offline during indexing and reused across all queries, making retrieval cheap; it acts as a persistent associative index over the entire corpus.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "synonymy_edges",
        "title": "Connecting the Dots with Synonymy",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- embedding similarity\n- threshold 0.8\n\nA retrieval encoder computes similarity between all node pairs; pairs above the 0.8 threshold receive a synonymy edge, allowing the graph to connect mentions of the same entity even when phrased differently.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "personalized_pagerank",
        "title": "One-Step Multi-hop with PageRank",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- seed query nodes\n- probability propagation\n\nPPR initializes the random walk distribution at query-named-entity nodes, so probability mass flows only through graph neighborhoods relevant to the query, achieving multi-hop reasoning in a single pass.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "node_specificity",
        "title": "Weighting What Matters",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- inverse passage count\n- local IDF\n\nNode specificity = 1 / (number of passages containing the node), a local analogue of inverse document frequency that prevents common, uninformative nodes from dominating PPR scores.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "Node specificity down-weights nodes that appear in many passages. Which classic NLP concept is this analogous to? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "TF-IDF's IDF component",
        "BM25's term frequency",
        "Cosine similarity"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "TF-IDF's IDF component",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
    },
